<Author>lapintura
<Content>a retreat in the big city Well, to begin, the hotel is lovely. From the floral-covered entrance to the door of each room, it鈥檚 just what one would hope for. The photos on their website are very accurate, at least for my room. So I am including other views of the room. I notice that a previous review included a photo of a not-so-lovely view from the room. Frankly, I was too taken with the decor of my suite to care about a view. I am an artist and was intrigued to see in which 鈥渁rtist鈥檚 suite鈥?I would be staying. As it turned out, it was Maria Izquierdo, a 20th century female artist known for paintings of women and children. I was disappointed that, in the very nice collection of art books in my room, there was not one on the artist herself. That would have been a nice touch. I was traveling alone to Mexico City and I was only staying one night at Casa Vieja but I would return without hesitation. The staff was helpful and I appreciated that the person who greeted me spoke English well enough that I could communicate with her about a restaurant and a taxi to the airport. The location of the hotel is ideal for shopping and museums. And best of all, Colonia Polanco has amazing restaurants so the very nice kitchen area probably would not get much use. Now that I know there is such a nice place waiting for me, it will make a perfect retreat at the end of a day of exploring DF. One caution: be prepared for the hotel taxes when budgeting for your stay. Also, not all of the staff speaks even a little English so learn some basic Spanish before you go. It will make the entire experience easier. 
